About Those CAA Layoffs=E2=80=A6

The long-awaited CAA layoffs hit on Friday, and they were mostly as predict=
ed. The total at Hollywood=E2=80=99s biggest and most influential talent ag=
ency, for now, is about 30=E2=80=94largely in the motion picture and televi=
sion departments. That=E2=80=99s a small blip on the surface of the Death S=
tar, which employs about 3,500 people worldwide=E2=80=94though more agents =
have been given the boot and also the courtesy of some time to go elsewhere=
, if they can. (Josh Pearl, a veteran comedy agent, landed at Mosaic as a m=
anager today. There are a few more I won=E2=80=99t name because they=E2=80=
=99re still scrambling.)

Of the group that=E2=80=99s public, I think senior TV literary agents Joel =
Begleiter and Adam Biren are the most surprising, both because they were gi=
ven zero warning and were generally productive and liked. More reductions a=
re almost certainly
coming in the new year, per sources, and reviews and bonus conversations wi=
ll be brutal. (CAA declined to comment.)

Honestly, I=E2=80=99m a little surprised there weren=E2=80=99t more cuts. C=
AA, and all of the major talent agencies, were built for an entertainment b=
usiness that no longer exists: Cable TV is dead, pilot season is dead, the =
rest of broadcast is teetering, and the streaming model doesn=E2=80=99t pro=
duce nearly the kind of long-term hits that pay for all those agents, with =
their assistants and set visits and lunches at Nerano. The Writers Guild ki=
lled packaging, which means the studios now keep the fees that used to go t=
o the agencies, and that loss is only going to worsen as the spigot of past=
 packages slowly runs dry. Last year=E2=80=99s strikes exacerbated the decl=
ine in series and movies being made, and, given the growth in audience and =
monetization of user-generated content, that decline may be forever. Fewer =
shows and movies, less talent needed for those
shows and movies, fewer traditional film and TV agents needed to service th=
at talent. Easy math.

CAA has specific issues, too. It operates on an October-to-October fiscal c=
alendar, meaning that the period just completed was particularly decimated =
by the strikes, which ended in September but didn=E2=80=99t lead to an upti=
ck in production until well into 2024. In its 2022 acquisition of rival ICM=
 Partners, CAA took on all those agents and employees to get the publishing=
 and sports divisions it wanted, as well as the three ICM showrunners who a=
ctually matter. At the time, the bulk wasn=E2=80=99t a big concern, and wit=
h that extra EBITDA, C.E.O. Bryan Lourd was able to generate the $7 billion=
 valuation he coveted in last year=E2=80=99s sale of owner TPG=E2=80=99s st=
ake, which allowed him and partners Richard Lovett and Kevin Huvane to extr=
act hundreds of millions of dollars. But in the changed landscape, the bulk=
 has become more like deadweight, and CAA=E2=80=99s new parent
company, the family office of Kering fashion mogul Fran=C3=A7ois-Henri Pina=
ult, is far from immune to the general slowdown in the luxury market. It pe=
riodically squeezes CAA on costs, per sources.

CAA certainly isn=E2=80=99t alone here. Rival UTA has undergone its own rec=
ent layoffs, and WME is now caught up in parent Endeavor=E2=80=99s ongoing =
and somewhat tragicomic effort to take the whole company private after spen=
ding years trying to go public. Endeavor C.E.O. Ari Emanuel announced a com=
plex deal today to buy out Endeavor assets OpenBets and IMG Arena and put t=
hem in a separate, management-owned entity. That kind of asset-building is =
what Ari cares about most, not the stagnating Hollywood representation busi=
ness. To these Big Three diversified agencies, with sports and branding and=
 books and chefs and influencers, so few individual clients actually matter=
 now, and because of that, so few agents actually matter, too.

And this is a more
uncomfortable topic, but the decades-old agency apprenticeship model=E2=80=
=94toil on someone=E2=80=99s desk, get promoted, join the team for a few bi=
g clients and then, if you=E2=80=99re lucky, develop your own=E2=80=94has p=
roduced a ton of junior and mid-level reps that, in a challenged market, ju=
st aren=E2=80=99t good enough. Or at least they don=E2=80=99t sign or take =
over enough of their own clients. They=E2=80=99re servicers, =E2=80=9Con th=
e team,=E2=80=9D which is a CAA hallmark and is fine when there are tons of=
 high-commission clients to service. But less fine when the revenue=E2=80=
=94and the entertainment business in general=E2=80=94no longer justifies th=
e big team.

