The Wednesday-Sunday Window

For the first time since 2018, this year=E2=80=99s mid-November slate might=
 mimic the box office pattern from the prior two decades, at least in terms=
 of overall grosses for the pre-Thanksgiving YA fantasy flick and the holid=
ay weekend Disney toon. And like most such Turkey Day showdowns in the 2000=
s and especially the 2010s, it could be an everybody-wins weekend.

Traditionally, Thanksgiving was topped not by the holiday tentpole, but by =
the young adult sensation flick opening the week prior. In most years, when=
 a YA fantasy franchise movie (such as one of the Twilight sequels) opened =
the weekend before the holiday, that film=E2=80=99s second weekend would be=
at the opening weekend of the holiday=E2=80=99s big opener, be it a Disney =
toon or otherwise. In 2019, Disney slotted Frozen II the week before Thanks=
giving, positioning it as the YA
fantasy flick and the family-friendly animated feature of the season. It wo=
rked.

However, then and presumably now, there=E2=80=99s room for multiple winners=
 during what might look like a contested weekend. In 2013, The Hunger Games=
: Catching Fire earned $100 million in its Wednesday-Sunday =E2=80=9Csecond=
 weekend=E2=80=9D (after opening to $158 million), while the first Frozen w=
ent wide for a $93 million Wednesday-Sunday debut. Catching Fire would beco=
me that year=E2=80=99s biggest domestic earner ($425 million), while Frozen=
 topped the worldwide list with $1.3 billion. Neither Lionsgate nor Disney =
had any reason to complain.

In 2010, Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part I beat Tangled over the=
 long Thanksgiving weekend ($75 million versus $67 million) and in overall =
grosses ($960 million versus $600 million). Both Warner Bros. and Disney we=
re happy with their respective results.

Rising Tides Lifting All Boats?

Heading into the holiday season, Moana 2 is tracking to crush the $125 mill=
ion Wednesday-Sunday haul for Frozen II (earned in its second weekend, foll=
owing its $130 million debut in 2019) to net a new Thanksgiving record. Eve=
n if the animated sequel ends up looking and feeling like a Disney+ series =
pretzeled into a theatrical sequel, strong 2010s nostalgia for Disney title=
s=E2=80=94think Avatar: The Way of Water, Inside Out 2, and Deadpool & Wolv=
erine=E2=80=94has been kicking butt the past two years.

Meanwhile, enthusiasm for Wicked should continue to build among fans of the=
 Broadway show between now and opening day. Those interested in movie-speci=
fic hooks, like pop star Ariana Grande in a scene-stealing comic turn, will=
 also tune in. Interestingly, Gladiator II was essentially tied with
Wicked for overall interest (as of this writing ( https://deadline.com/2024=
/10/wicked-gladiator-ii-box-office-opening-1236163352/?utm_campaign=3DWhat+=
I%27m+Hearing+-+SUBSCRIBERS+%2811%2F11%2F24%29&utm_source=3Dcustomer.io )) =
among women.

Could the frequently shirtless Paul Mescal and co-star Pedro Pascal draw ot=
herwise interested female audiences (and their male companions) away from W=
icked on opening weekend and over the holiday? Sure, but the fact that its =
audience skewed 80 percent female didn=E2=80=99t hurt the $142 million open=
ing of The Twilight Saga: New Moon in November 2009. History has shown that=
 a demographic ceiling matters less if the ceiling is high enough.

It would be encouraging if Disney=E2=80=99s first big Thanksgiving hit of t=
he 2020s weren=E2=80=99t a sequel, but alas=E2=80=A6 Hopefully, C.E.O.
Bob Iger remembers that you can=E2=80=99t (theoretically, not a prediction)=
 make $1 billion off Moana 2 without rolling the dice on (and being satisfi=
ed with a $643 million global total for) an original movie=E2=80=94like, sa=
y, Moana, in 2016. Similarly, whether Wicked: Part One or Moana 2 comes out=
 on top, Universal might get more of a benefit from a =E2=80=9Cnew=E2=80=9D=
 franchise in Wicked. After all, Moana 2=E2=80=99s success won=E2=80=99t ch=
ange the narrative over Disney=E2=80=99s reliance on previously successful =
properties. If that=E2=80=99s the conversation we=E2=80=99re having on Dece=
mber 2, it will be good news for all invested parties.

Finally=E2=80=A6 Some Fun Stuff=E2=80=A6

I used to occasionally compile interesting social moments and dining sighti=
ngs and randomly amusing items, but I stopped during the strikes. Now, as a=
 post-election pick-me-up, I=E2=80=99ll occasionally bring back the fun stu=
ff segment, as long as you send me items at Matt@puck.news=E2=80=A6

Sony film chief Tom Rothman chose Leo DiCaprio=E2=80=99s Rick Dalton from O=
nce Upon a Time=E2=80=A6 in Hollywood (leather jacket included, of course!)=
 as his costume for his big 70th birthday party at the Rainbow Room in NYC.=
 Guests were instructed to come as a character from a movie Rothman release=
d=E2=80=94alas, there were no Madame Webs in attendance, reports one attend=
ee=E2=80=94and the guest list did not include many of his Sony colleagues i=
n L.A., nor his new boss, incoming C.E.O. Ravi Ahuja. =E2=80=A6 A reluctant=
 congrats to WME for winning the
Entertainment Softball League=E2=80=99s summer championship (my team was sa=
dly bounced in the first round of the playoffs). =E2=80=A6 Michael B. Jorda=
n was lunching with Ayo Edibiri at the Polo Lounge. Ousted Warner Bros. C.E=
=2EO. Kevin Tsujihara sat in a bo=
oth nearby. =E2=80=A6 Disney=E2=80=99s Bob I=
ger raised a few eyebrows dining with Universal=E2=80=99s Donna Langley at =
Toscana a few weeks ago. (They=E2=80=99re friends.) Iger also got a persona=
l tour from Comcast frenemy Brian Roberts of the new Universal buildings on=
 the lot last month. =E2=80=A6 Yes, Wicked producer Marc Platt appeared to =
momentarily forget the name of co-star (and Ariana Grande=E2=80=99s boyfrie=
nd!) Ethan Slater onstage when introducing the cast at the L.A. premiere. (=
The film=E2=80=99s good, BTW.)

