          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The long-awaited CA=
A layoffs hit on Friday, and they were mostly as predicted. The total at Ho=
llywood=E2=80=99s biggest and most influential talent agency, for now, is a=
bout 30=E2=80=94largely in the motion picture and television departments. T=
hat=E2=80=99s a small blip on the surface of the Death Star, which employs =
about 3,500 people worldwide=E2=80=94though more agents have been given the=
 boot and also the courtesy of some time to go elsewhere, if they can. (<b>=
Josh Pearl</b>, a veteran comedy agent, landed at Mosaic as a manager today=
=2E There are a few more I won=E2=80=99=
t name because they=E2=80=99re still s=
crambling.) <br/><br/>Of the group that=E2=80=99s public, I think senior TV=
 literary agents <b>Joel Begleiter</b> and <b>Adam Biren</b> are the most s=
urprising, both because they were given zero warning and were generally pro=
ductive and liked. More reductions are almost certainly
coming in the new year, per sources, and reviews and bonus conversations wi=
ll be brutal. (CAA declined to comment.)<br/> <br/>Honestly, I=E2=80=99m a =
little surprised there weren=E2=80=99t <i>more </i>cuts. CAA, and all of th=
e major talent agencies, were built for an entertainment business that no l=
onger exists: Cable TV is dead, pilot season is dead, the rest of broadcast=
 is teetering, and the streaming model doesn=E2=80=99t produce nearly the k=
ind of long-term hits that pay for all those agents, with their assistants =
and set visits <i>and</i> lunches at Nerano. The Writers Guild killed packa=
ging, which means the studios now keep the fees that used to go to the agen=
cies, and that loss is only going to worsen as the spigot of past packages =
slowly runs dry. Last year=E2=80=99s strikes exacerbated the decline in ser=
ies and movies being made, and, given the growth in audience and monetizati=
on of user-generated content, that decline may be forever. Fewer shows and =
movies, less talent needed for those
shows and movies, fewer traditional film and TV agents needed to service th=
at talent. Easy math.  <br/> <br/>CAA has specific issues, too. It operates=
 on an October-to-October fiscal calendar, meaning that the period just com=
pleted was particularly decimated by the strikes, which ended in September =
but didn=E2=80=99t lead to an uptick in production until well into 2024. In=
 its 2022 acquisition of rival ICM Partners, CAA took on all those agents a=
nd employees to get the publishing and sports divisions it wanted, as well =
as the three ICM showrunners who actually matter. At the time, the bulk was=
n=E2=80=99t a big concern, and with that extra EBITDA, C.E.O. <b>Bryan Lour=
d</b> was able to generate the $7 billion valuation he coveted in last year=
=E2=80=99s sale of owner TPG=E2=80=99s stake, which allowed him and partner=
s <b>Richard Lovett</b> and <b>Kevin Huvane</b> to extract hundreds of mill=
ions of dollars. But in the changed landscape, the bulk has become more lik=
e deadweight, and CAA=E2=80=99s new parent
company, the family office of Kering fashion mogul <b>Fran=C3=A7ois-Henri P=
inault</b>, is far from immune to the general slowdown in the luxury market=
=2E It periodically squeezes CAA on cos=
ts, per sources.   <br/> <br/>CAA cert=
ainly isn=E2=80=99t alone here. Rival UTA has undergone its own recent layo=
ffs, and WME is now caught up in parent Endeavor=E2=80=99s ongoing and some=
what tragicomic effort to take the whole company private after spending yea=
rs trying to go public. Endeavor C.E.O. <b>Ari Emanuel</b> announced a comp=
lex deal today to buy out Endeavor assets OpenBets and IMG Arena and put th=
em in a separate, management-owned entity. That kind of asset-building is w=
hat Ari cares about most, not the stagnating Hollywood representation busin=
ess. To these Big Three diversified agencies, with sports and branding and =
books and chefs and influencers, so few individual clients actually matter =
now, and because of that, so few <i>agents</i> actually matter, too.     <b=
r/> <br/>And this is a more
uncomfortable topic, but the decades-old agency apprenticeship model=E2=80=
=94toil on someone=E2=80=99s desk, get promoted, join the team for a few bi=
g clients and then, if you=E2=80=99re lucky, develop your own=E2=80=94has p=
roduced a ton of junior and mid-level reps that, in a challenged market, ju=
st aren=E2=80=99t good enough. Or at least they don=E2=80=99t sign or take =
over enough of their own clients. They=E2=80=99re servicers, =E2=80=9Con th=
e team,=E2=80=9D which is a CAA hallmark and is fine when there are tons of=
 high-commission clients to service. But less fine when the revenue=E2=80=
=94and the entertainment business in general=E2=80=94no longer justifies th=
e big team.     <br/></td>
         </tr>
