         <tr class=3D"replica" name=3D"s8">
          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">The pre-Thanksgivin=
g trifecta of <i>Gladiator II, Wicked: Part One</i>, and <i>Moana 2</i> pro=
vides a veritable pre-Covid-esque theatrical cornucopia that should produce=
 pre-pandemic box office returns. As we=E2=80=99ve seen semi-regularly sinc=
e early 2021, theatrical tentpoles are crucial to bringing the overall mark=
etplace back. In short, if you release it, they will come.<br/><br/>By movi=
ng <i>Wicked </i>to the weekend before the holiday break, Universal is able=
 to position <b>Jon M. Chu</b>=E2=80=99s $145 million musical fantasy, base=
d on the popular stage show seen by more than 65 million people, as this ye=
ar=E2=80=99s proverbial <i>Hunger Games-</i> or <i>Twilight</i>-sized YA bl=
ockbuster. <i>Moana</i>, for its part, is the most watched film of all time=
 on Disney+. If the theatrical industry has returned to normalcy, both movi=
es should do serious box office.
<br/><br/>Official tracking has <i>Wicked </i>opening around $90 million an=
d <i>Moana 2 </i>earning as much as $135 million over its Wednesday-Sunday =
Thanksgiving weekend debut frame. Buzz for <i>Wicked </i>is also growing, w=
ith presales among its female-centric fan base likely to increase as word s=
preads on social media and the review embargo drops. Overseas tracking is l=
ess certain, but <i>Wicked </i>has earned $5 billion worldwide as a stage m=
usical, and <i>Moana</i> is an A-level Disney princess property worldwide. =
Even many of Disney=E2=80=99s underwhelming 2020s animated films pulled str=
ong overseas-skewing splits. <i>Wish </i>wasn=E2=80=99t a =E2=80=9Chit,=E2=
=80=9D but it did generate 75 percent of its $255 million worldwide cume ou=
tside of North America.<br/><br/>Meanwhile, in a typical year, <b>Ridley Sc=
ott</b>=E2=80=99s well-reviewed <i>Gladiator II</i> might have opened in <i=
>early</i> November=E2=80=94like Scott=E2=80=99s <i>American Gangster, </i>=
in 2007, which starred <i>Gladiator II</i>=E2=80=99s <b>Denzel
Washington</b> alongside former <i>Gladiator </i>headliner <b>Russell Crowe=
</b>. However, Hollywood mostly avoided the weeks before and after Election=
 Day, so it, too, is playing in the holiday sandbox. Thanks to its larger b=
udget, <i>Gladiator II</i> now has to fill the role of both adult-skewing c=
ounterprogramming option=E2=80=94see also: <i>Knives Out </i>in 2019 or Den=
zel=E2=80=99s <i>Deja Vu </i>in 2006=E2=80=94and a tentpole unto itself. As=
 of this writing, the $250 million, R-rated actioner is tracking for an est=
imated $65 million domestic debut. I=E2=80=99ve heard that the overseas tra=
cking is strong, suggesting that the movie might be an example of nostalgia=
-skewing I.P. that <i>succeeds</i> in other territories, unlike <i>Twisters=
 </i>and (relatively speaking) <i>Beetlejuice Beetlejuice</i>. <br/></td>
