          <td style=3D"padding-bottom: 36px; color: #000000; font-size: 16p=
x; line-height: 30px; margin-top: 0; margin-bottom: 0;">For the first time =
since 2018, this year=E2=80=99s mid-November slate might mimic the box offi=
ce pattern from the prior two decades, at least in terms of overall grosses=
 for the pre-Thanksgiving YA fantasy flick and the holiday weekend Disney t=
oon. And like most such Turkey Day showdowns in the 2000s and especially th=
e 2010s, it could be an everybody-wins weekend.<br/><br/>Traditionally, Tha=
nksgiving was topped not by the holiday tentpole, but by the young adult se=
nsation flick opening the week <i>prior</i>. In most years, when a YA fanta=
sy franchise movie (such as one of the <i>Twilight </i>sequels) opened the =
weekend before the holiday, that film=E2=80=99s second weekend would beat t=
he opening weekend of the holiday=E2=80=99s big opener, be it a Disney toon=
 or otherwise. In 2019, Disney slotted <i>Frozen II </i>the week before Tha=
nksgiving, positioning it as the YA
fantasy flick <i>and</i> the family-friendly animated feature of the season=
=2E It worked. <br/><br/>However, th=
en and presumably now, there=E2=80=99s ro=
om for multiple winners during what might look like a contested weekend. In=
 2013, <i>The Hunger Games: Catching Fire </i>earned $100 million in its We=
dnesday-Sunday =E2=80=9Csecond weekend=E2=80=9D (after opening to $158 mill=
ion), while the first <i>Frozen </i>went wide for a $93 million Wednesday-S=
unday debut. <i>Catching Fire </i>would become that year=E2=80=99s biggest =
domestic earner ($425 million), while <i>Frozen </i>topped the worldwide li=
st with $1.3 billion. Neither Lionsgate nor Disney had any reason to compla=
in. <br/><br/>In 2010, <i>Harry Potter and the Deathly Hallows: Part I</i> =
beat <i>Tangled </i>over the long Thanksgiving weekend ($75 million versus =
$67 million) and in overall grosses ($960 million versus $600 million). Bot=
h Warner Bros. and Disney were happy with their respective results.<br/></t=
d>
         </tr>
